'''Andy de la Tour''' (born 1948) is an English actor and [[screenwriter]].
In films he appeared in ''[[Plenty (film)|Plenty]]'', ''[[Notting Hill (film)|Notting Hill]]'', the [[Roman Polanski]] version of ''[[Oliver Twist]]'','' 44" Chest'' and ''[[The Confessions (film)|The Confessions]]'', and in television ''[[The Young Ones (TV series)|The Young Ones]]'', ''[[Bottom (TV series)|Bottom]]'', ''[[Kavanagh QC]]'' and ''[[The Brief (ITV)|The Brief]]''. On stage he has appeared at the National Theatre in Harold Pinter's ''No Man's Land'' and Alan Bennett's ''People''.
His credits as a television writer include ''[[Boon (TV series)|Boon]]'', ''[[Lovejoy]]'', ''[[Peak Practice]]'', ''The Vet'', ''Kavanagh QC'' and ''Clem''. He wrote the stage play ''Safe In Our Hands'' (winner of the LWT Plays on Stage Award).<ref>Nobbs, David (2004) ''I Didn't Get Where I am Today'', Arrow, {{ISBN|978-0099421641}}, p. 393</ref>
As a stand-up comedian he appeared in the 1980s with [[Rik Mayall]], [[Ben Elton]] and French and Saunders.<ref>"[http://www.edinburghnews.scotsman.com/what-s-on/theatre/andy-de-la-tour-fringe-summer-with-rik-mayall-1-3499617 Andy De La Tour: Fringe summer with Rik Mayall]", ''[[Edinburgh Evening News]]'', 5 August 2014. Retrieved 10 March 2016</ref> In 2012 he wrote ''Stand-Up or Die'' about his time as a stand-up comedian in New York.<ref>York, Melissa (2013) "[http://www.newhamrecorder.co.uk/news/features/andy_de_la_tour_joins_miles_jupp_to_discuss_adventure_in_stratford_1_2018558 Andy de la Tour joins Miles Jupp to discuss adventure in Stratford]", ''[[Newham Recorder]]'', 15 April 2013. Retrieved 10 March 2016</ref>
He is the brother of actress [[Frances de la Tour]].<ref>Double, Oliver (1997) ''Stand Up!'', Methuen Publishing, {{ISBN|978-0413703200}}, p. 176</ref>
He appeared as George Porter in episode 13 of series 31 of [[Casualty (TV series)|Casualty]] "Not in Holby Anymore" and as General Hurst Romodi<ref>https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0209426/</ref> in ''[[Rogue One]]: A Star Wars Story''.
On 6 June 2018 he appeared as Ted, an aging mechanic with a heart defect in BBC1's lunchtime soap "Doctors".
